T1  - Capital Taxation During the U.S. Great Depression
PY  - 2012
Y1  - 2012/08/01
DO  - 10.1093/qje/qjs022
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 127
IS  - 3
SP  - 1515
EP  - 1550
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - Previous studies of the U.S. Great Depression find that increased government spending and taxation contributed little to either the dramatic downturn or the slow recovery. These studies include only one type of capital taxation: a business profits tax. The contribution is much greater when the analysis includes other types of capital taxes. A general equilibrium model extended to include taxes on dividends, property, capital stock, excess profits, and undistributed profits predicts patterns of output, investment, and hours worked that are more like those in the 1930s than found in earlier studies. The greatest effects come from the increased taxes on corporate dividends and undistributed profits.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/qje/qjs022
ER  - 



